tionRevisions","id":"82001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82001"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent for review of a lesion on his right arm. The lesion has been present since birth and has not changed in size. It is painless and does not cause any functional impairment. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a well-circumscribed, raised, violaceous lesion on his right arm measuring 2 cm in diameter (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation only","Oral propranolol","Topical timolol","Surgical excision","Pulsed dye laser therapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with a congenital haemangioma, which is present from birth and distinct from infantile haemangiomas that typically appear in the first few weeks of life. Congenital haemangiomas are classified into rapidly involuting (RICH) and non-involuting (NICH) types.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation only\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for a rapidly involuting congenital haemangioma (RICH), as these typically resolve spontaneously by age 5 years. However, this lesion has shown no signs of involution over two years, suggesting it is likely a NICH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for a non-involuting congenital haemangioma (NICH) if treatment is desired. These lesions do not spontaneously resolve and surgical removal provides definitive treatment with good cosmetic results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral propranolol\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical timolol\u003C/strong\u003E are effective treatments for infantile haemangiomas but have no role in the management of congenital haemangiomas. These medications work by inducing vasoconstriction and inhibiting angiogenesis in actively proliferating lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulsed dye laser therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for superficial vascular lesions but is not the first-line treatment for congenital haemangiomas. It would be ineffective for deeper components of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is distinguishing between different types of vascular anomalies, as their natural history and treatment approaches vary significantly. Congenital haemangiomas that show no signs of involution by age 2 years are unlikely to resolve spontaneously and may benefit from surgical excision if treatment is desired.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Congenital haemangiomas are present at birth and are distinct from infantile haemangiomas","Most congenital haemangiomas undergo spontaneous involution by age 5 years","Non-involuting congenital haemangiomas (NICH) require surgical excision if treatment is desired"],"references":["Olsen GM, Nackers A, Drolet BA. Infantile and congenital hemangiomas. Semin Pediatr Surg. 2020;29(5):150969. doi:10.1016/j.sempedsurg.2020.150969","Krol A, MacArthur C. Congenital Hemangiomas. Archives of Facial Plastic Surgery. 2005;7(5):307-311."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2431"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20041"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20041"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d7ee467a-d790-4d5d-80c8-15025f969c8a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d7ee467a-d790-4d5d-80c8-15025f969c8a.jpg","isProc